Day 4 — JFrog CLI and REST API
JFrog CLI
The JFrog CLI (jf) is the primary command-line interface for interacting with Artifactory. It handles:

Uploading/downloading artifacts
Build integration (collecting build info)
Managing configurations
Running Xray scans
Managing repositories and permissions
CLI Configuration
The CLI uses server configurations — named profiles that store URL, credentials, and other settings. You can configure multiple servers (dev, staging, prod).
jf config add myserver \
  --url https://mycompany.jfrog.io \
  --user admin \
  --password mypassword
After configuration, all CLI commands implicitly use the configured server.

Upload Spec
The CLI uses File Specs — JSON documents describing what to upload/download and where. This decouples the operation from the CLI command.

{
  "files": [
    {
      "pattern": "build/output/*.jar",
      "target": "libs-release-local/com/mycompany/myapp/1.0.0/",
      "props": "build.number=42;env=prod"
    }
  ]
}

REST API
Artifactory has a comprehensive REST API for everything — creating repos, managing permissions, searching artifacts, getting build info. Used for automation and integration.

Key API endpoints:
GET  /artifactory/api/storage/{repoKey}/{path}     → file info
PUT  /artifactory/{repoKey}/{path}                 → upload artifact
GET  /artifactory/{repoKey}/{path}                 → download artifact
GET  /artifactory/api/build/{buildName}/{buildNumber} → build info
POST /artifactory/api/search/aql                  → AQL search

AQL (Artifactory Query Language)
A powerful query language to search artifacts by any property — name, repo, date, custom properties, build info, etc.

items.find({
  "repo": "libs-release-local",
  "@build.number": "42"
})

